   \'93The D&C mishap,\'94 said Bellows. \'93You remember, about eight days ago, the twenty-three-year-old girl.\'94\par
   \'93Well I hope not,\'94 said Harris, \'93but it\'92s beginning to look that way.\'94\par
   \'93What was the anesthesia?\'94 asked Bellows lifting Berman\'92s right eyelid and glancing down into the widely dilated pupil.\par
   \'93Neurolept anesthesia with nitrous,\'94 said Harris. \'93The girl\'92s was halothane. If the problem is the same clinically, it wasn\'92t the anesthetic agent.\'94 Harris looked up from the anesthesia record toward Goodman. \'93Why did you give this extra cc of Innovar toward the end of the case, Norman?\'94\par
   Dr. Goodman did not respond immediately. Dr. Harris called his name again.\par
   \'93The patient seemed to be getting too light,\'94 said Goodman, suddenly breaking his trance.\par
   \'93But why Innovar so late in the case? Wouldn\'92t fentanyl alone have been more prudent?\'94\par
   \'93Probably. I should have used the fentanyl alone. The Innovar was just handy and I knew that I\'92d only use an additional cc.\'94\par
   \'93Can\'92t something be done?\'94 asked Susan with a hint of desperation. Images of Nancy Greenly streamed back with bits and pieces of the recent conversation with Berman. She could distinctly remember his vitality, which was in sharp contrast to the waxy, lifeless-appearing figure before her.\par
   \'93It\'92s been done, whatever it was,\'94 said Harris with finality, returning the anesthesia record to Goodman. \'93All we can do now is watch and see what kind of cerebral function returns, if any. The pupils are widely dilated and they do not react to light. That is not a good sign, to say the least. It probably means that there was extensive brain death.\'94\par
   Susan experienced a sickening feeling rise up within herself. She shuddered and the feeling passed but she felt lightheaded. Above all, she felt helplessly desperate.\par
   \'93This is too much,\'94 said Susan suddenly and with obvious emotion. Her voice quivered. \'93A normal healthy man with a minor peripheral problem ends up like a ... like a vegetable. My God, this can\'92t go on. Two young people within just a couple of weeks. I mean, it\'92s an unacceptable risk. Why doesn\'92t the Chief of Anesthesia close the department? Something\'92s got to be wrong. It\'92s absurd to allow ...\'94\par
