   \'93Well then, don\'92t think about it. Come on, we\'92ve got to get moving.\'94\par
   \'93Wait a minute. You know what I\'92m going to do?\'94\par
   \'93I can\'92t guess and I\'92m not sure I want to know.\'94\par
   \'93I\'92m going to look into this particular problem. Six cases. That should be enough for some reasonable conclusions. I do have a third-year paper to do and I think I owe that much to Sean here.\'94\par
   \'93Oh for Christ sake, Susan, let\'92s not be melodramatic.\'94\par
   \'93I\'92m not being melodramatic. I think I\'92m responding to a challenge. Sean challenged me earlier with my image of myself as a doctor. I failed. I wasn\'92t detached or professional. You might even say I acted like a schoolgirl. Now I\'92m challenged again. But this time intellectually with a problem, a serious problem. Maybe I can respond to this challenge in a more commendable fashion. Maybe these cases represent a new symptom complex or disease process. Maybe they represent a new complication of anesthesia because of some peculiar susceptibility these people had from some previous insult which they suffered in the past.\'94\par
