   He was impeccably dressed in a beige suit tailored to fit close to his lean body, accented by an orange silk scarf in his left breast pocket. His graying hair was moderately long and brushed back from his high forehead, just covering the tops of his ears. His face was aristocratic, with sharp features and a thin nose. He wore executive half-glasses framed in delicate reddish tortoiseshell. His green eyes rapidly scanned back and forth across the sheet of paper in his hand.\par
   Susan would have been greatly intimidated by a combination of the impressive surroundings and Stark\'92s awe-inspiring reputation as a surgical genius had it not been for his initial smile and his seemingly incongruous posture. The fact that he had his feet up on the corner of the desk made Susan feel more comfortable, as if Stark really didn\'92t take his power position within the hospital too seriously. Susan correctly surmised that his skill as a surgeon and his ability as a medical administrator-businessman made it possible for Stark to ignore conventional executive posturing. Stark finished reading the paper and looked up at Susan sitting in front of him.\par
   \'93That, young lady, is very interesting. Obviously I am totally aware of the surgical cases, but I had no idea a similar problem was occurring on the medical floors. Whether they are indeed related is uncertain but I must give you credit for coming up with the idea that they may be related. And these two recent respiratory arrests and deaths; associating them is ... well, both far-out and brilliant at the same time. It gives food for thought. You have related them because you feel that depression of respiration is the common ground for all the cases. My first reaction to that\'97now, this is just my first reaction\'97is that it does not explain the anesthesia cases because in that circumstance, the respiratory pattern is being artificially maintained. You suggest some previous encephalitis or brain infection making people more susceptible to complications during anesthesia ... let me see.\'94\par
   Stark swung his feet from his desk and turned toward the window. Unconsciously he took his reading glasses from his nose and lightly chewed one of the earpieces. His eyes narrowed in concentration.\par
   \'93Parkinsonism has now been related to previous unsuspected viral insult, so I suppose your theory is possible. But how could it be proved?\'94\par
   Stark rotated around, facing Susan.\par
   \'93And you must be assured that we investigated the anesthesia complication cases ad nauseam. Everything\'97and I mean everything\'97was studied with a fine-tooth comb by a host of people, anesthesiologists, epidemiologists, internists, surgeons ... everybody we could think of. Except, of course, a medical student.\'94\par
   Stark smiled warmly and Susan found herself responding to the man\'92s renowned charisma.\par
   \'93I believe,\'94 said Susan, her confidence rallying, \'93the study should start with the central computer bank. The computer information I obtained was only for the past year and called up by an indirect method. I have no idea what data would emerge if the computer was asked directly for all cases over, say, the last five years of respiratory depression, coma, and unexplained death.\par
   \'93Then with a complete list of the potentially related cases, the charts would have to be painstakingly reviewed to try to elicit any common denominators. The families of the involved patients would have to be interviewed to obtain the best possible record of previous viral illness and patterns of illnesses. The other task would be to obtain serum from all existing cases for antibody screens.\'94\par
   Susan watched Stark\'92s face, intently preparing herself for an untoward response like that she had experienced with Nelson and then more dramatically with Harris. In contrast, Stark maintained an even expression, obviously in thought over Susan\'92s suggestions. It was apparent that he had an open, innovative mind. Finally he spoke.\par
   \'93Shotgun-style antibody screening is not very productive; it is time-consuming and it is horribly expensive.\'94\par
   \'93Counter-immunoelectrophoresis techniques have relieved some of these disadvantages,\'94 offered Susan, encouraged by Stark\'92s response.\par
   \'93Perhaps, but it still would represent an enormous outlay of capital with a very low probability of positive results. I\'92d have to have some specific evidence before I could justify that type of resource commitment. But maybe you should suggest this to Dr. Nelson, down in Medicine. Immunology is his special field.\'94\par
   \'93I don\'92t think Dr. Nelson would be interested,\'94 said Susan.\par
   \'93Why is that?\'94\par
   \'93I haven\'92t the faintest idea. To tell the truth, I already spoke with Dr. Nelson. So I already know he\'92s not interested. And he wasn\'92t the only one. I mentioned my ideas to another department head and I thought I was going to get swatted like some naughty child that needed chastising. Trying to incorporate that episode into the whole picture, I get a feeling that something else could be operating here.\'94\par
   \'93And what is that?\'94 asked Stark, glancing over the figures Susan had provided.\par
   \'93Well, I don\'92t know what word to use ... foul play ... or something sinister.\'94\par
   Susan stopped talking quite suddenly, expecting either laughter or anger. But Stark merely rotated in his chair, looking out over the city again.\par
   \'93Foul play. You do have an imagination, Dr. Wheeler, no doubt about that.\'94\par
   Stark turned back toward the room, rising up and walking around his desk.\par
   \'93Foul play,\'94 he repeated. \'93I must admit I\'92d never even considered that.\'94 Stark had been briefed only that morning about Cowley\'92s discovery of the drugs in locker 338; that information had disturbed him. He leaned against his desk and looked down at Susan.\par
   \'93If you think about foul play, motive becomes of paramount importance. And there just isn\'92t any motive for such a series of heartbreaking episodes. They are too dissimilar. And coma? You\'92d have to implicate some very clever psychopath operating on a premise that\'92s beyond rationality. But the biggest problem with the idea of foul play is that it would be impossible in the OR. There are too many people involved who are watching the patient too closely.\par
   \'93Certainly investigative activities should be carried out with an open mind, but I don\'92t think foul play is possible in this instance. But, I must admit, I had not thought of it.\'94\par
   \'93Actually,\'94 said Susan, \'93I hadn\'92t planned on suggesting foul play to you, but I\'92m glad that I did so that I can forget it. But back to the problem itself. If antibody screening is too expensive, the chart review and interviews would, be comparatively cheap. I could take that on myself, except I\'92d need a little help from you.\'94\par
   \'93What kind of help?\'94\par
   \'93First of all, I\'92d need to have authorization to use the computer. That\'92s number one. Secondly, I\'92d need authorization to get the charts. Thirdly, I may have run into a problem downstairs.\'94\par
   \'93What kind of a problem?\'94\par
   \'93Dr. Harris. He\'92s the one who blew his cool. I think he intends to have my surgical rotation here at the Memorial cut short. It seems that he is not fond of women in medicine, and perhaps I have served to underline that prejudice.\'94\par
   \'93Dr. Harris can be difficult to get along with. He\'92s an emotional type. But at the same time he\'92s probably the best mind in anesthesiology in the country. So don\'92t damn him until you see his other side. I believe he has specific personal reasons for his attitude toward women in medicine. It\'92s not admirable, perhaps, but it is potentially understandable. Anyway, I\'92ll see what I can do for you. At the same time I must tell you that you have picked a very touchy subject to become involved in. You have undoubtedly considered the malpractice implication, the potential bad publicity for the hospital and even the Boston medical community. Tread lightly, young lady, if you choose to tread at all. You\'92ll make no friends on the course you are embarking on, and it\'92s my opinion you should drop the whole affair. If you choose to go on, I\'92ll try to help you, although I can guarantee nothing. If you do turn up any information, I will be happy to offer an opinion. Obviously the more information you have, the easier it will be for me to get you what you need.\'94\par
   Stark moved toward the door from his office, opening it.\par
   \'93Give me a call later this afternoon and I\'92ll let you know if I\'92ve had any luck with your requests.\'94\par
   \'93Thank you for your time, Dr. Stark.\'94 Susan hesitated in the doorway, looking at Stark. \'93It is reassuring that you have not lived up to your reputation of being a man-, or should I say, woman-eater.\'94\par
   \'93Perhaps you will agree with the others when you find time to come on teaching rounds,\'94 said Stark, with a laugh.\par
   Susan said goodbye and left. Stark returned to his desk and spoke into his intercom, talking to his secretary.\par
   \'93Call Dr. Chandler and see if he has talked with Dr. Bellows yet. Tell him that I want to get to the bottom of those drugs in the locker room as soon as possible.\'94\par
   Stark turned and looked out over the complex of buildings that made up the Memorial. His life was so closely linked to the hospital that at certain points they merged. As Bellows had told Susan, Stark had personally raised an enormous amount\'92 of the money it had taken to revitalize the hospital and build its seven new buildings. It was partly due to his fund-raising abilities that he was Chief of Surgery at the Memorial.\par
   The more he thought about the drugs in 338 and their possible implications, the angrier he got. It was just another glaring example of how people in general could not be trusted to think in terms of the long-run effects.\par
   \'93Christ,\'94 he said out loud, his eyes mesmerized by the swirling snow clouds. Fools could undermine all his efforts at insuring the Memorial\'92s position as the number one hospital in the country. Years of work could go down the drain. It underscored his belief that he had to attend to everything if he wanted it done right.\par
Tuesday, February 24, 7:20 P.M.\par
The gloom of the winter Boston night had long since invaded the city when Susan alighted from the Harvard line train at the open-air Charles Street MBTA station. The wind, still blowing in from the Arctic, whistled in the river end of the station and traversed the length of the platform in short turbulent gusts. Susan bent over as she headed toward the stairs. The train lunged and slid out of the station, passing her on her right, its wheels screeching as it turned into the tunnel.\par
   Susan used the pedestrian overpass to cross the intersection of Charles Street and Cambridge Street. Underneath, the traffic had dissipated to a minor dribble of cars, but the noxious odor of exhaust gases still fouled the night air. Susan descended to Charles Street. In front of the all-night drugstore there was the usual collection of wayward individuals, either drunk or stoned. Several of them reached toward Susan, asking for spare change. She responded by quickening her step. Then she collided with a seedy, bearded fellow who had deliberately stepped into her way.\par
   \'93Real Paper or Phoenix, beautiful?\'94 asked the bearded fellow with seborrheic eyelids. He held several newspapers in his right hand.\par
   Susan recoiled, then pressed on, ignoring the lurid jibes and laughter of the night people. She passed down Charles Street and presently the surroundings changed. A few antique shop windows beckoned for her to dally, but the cold night wind urged her on. At Mount Vernon Street she turned up to the left and began to ascend Beacon Hill. From the numbers on the doors she knew she had a way to go. She passed Louisburg Square. The orange glow from the mullioned windows cast warm rays in the cold night. The houses gave a sense of peace and security behind their solid brick facades.\par
   Bellows\'92s apartment was in a building on the left, about a hundred yards beyond Louisburg Square. The buildings along here sat back behind small lawns and towering elms. Susan pushed open a squeaking metal gate and went up the stone steps to the heavy paneled door. In the foyer she blew on her blue fingers while walking in place to encourage circulation in her feet. She always had cold feet and hands from November to March. While she blew and stamped she scanned the names next to the buzzer. Bellows was number five. She pushed the button hard, and was rewarded with a raucous buzz.\par
   In a minor panic she reached for the doorknob, scraping her knuckle on the metallic guard on the door frame as the door swung open. A small amount of blood oozed from her knuckle, and she lifted her hand to her mouth. In front of her was a staircase twisting up to the left. A shining brass chandelier hovered above, and a gilded frame mirror served to make the hall seem more spacious. By reflex she checked her hair in the mirror, pressing it down at her temples. As she climbed she noticed attractively framed Brueghel prints on every landing.\par
   Exaggerating her exhaustion, she reached the top flight and paused, gripping the banister. Down the stairwell she could see to the tiled floor of the foyer, five storeys below. Bellows opened his door before Susan knocked.\par
   \'93There\'92s an oxygen bottle in here if you need it, Grandma,\'94 he said, smiling.\par
   \'93God, the air is thin up here. Maybe I should sit here on the steps and. recuperate for a few moments.\'94\par
   \'93A glass of Bordeaux will fix you up perfectly. Give me your hand.\'94\par
   Susan allowed Mark to help her into his apartment. Then she took off her coat, her eyes wandering around the room. Mark disappeared into the kitchen, returning with two glasses of ruby red wine.\par
   Susan threw her coat over a straight-back chair near the door and pulled oft her high boots. Distracted, she took the wine and sipped it. Her attention had been captured by the room she found herself in.\par
   \'93Pretty tastefully decorated for a surgeon,\'94 said Susan, walking into the center of the room.\par
   It was about twenty by forty feet. At each end was a large old-fashioned fireplace, and in each glowed a cheerful fire. The beamed cathedral ceiling was very high, perhaps twenty feet at the peak, slanting down toward both fireplaces. The far wall was an enormous complex of geometric shapes, some housing bookshelves, others with objets d\'92art and a large stereo, TV, and tape system. The near wall was of exposed brick and covered with paintings, lithographs, and medieval sheet music, attractively framed. An antique Howard clock ticked unobtrusively over the fireplace to the right, a ship model adorned the mantelpiece to the left. Through the windows, on either side of both fireplaces, a myriad of crooked chimneys was silhouetted against the night sky.\par
   The furnishings were of a minimum; Bellows had relied on a collection of thick scatter rugs, dominated by a blue and cream Bukhara in the center of the room. On it was a low onyx coffee table, surrounded by a large number of sizable pillows covered in shocking shades of corduroy.\par
   \'93This is beautiful,\'94 said Susan twisting around in the center of the room and then collapsing on an armful of cushions. \'93I never expected anything like this.\'94\par
   \'93What did you expect?\'94 Mark sat down on the other side of the low table.\par
   \'93An apartment. You know, tables, chairs, couch, the usual.\'94\par
   They both laughed, aware that they really did not know each other very well. Conversation remained on a frivolous level as they enjoyed the wine. Susan hopefully pointed her stocking feet toward the fire, to warm her toes.\par
   \'93More wine, Susan?\'94\par
   \'93For sure. It tastes wonderful.\'94\par
   Mark disappeared into the kitchen for the bottle. He poured each of them another glass.\par
   \'93No one would ever believe the day I\'92ve had today, incredible,\'94 said Susan, holding the glass of wine between her eye and the fire and appreciating its deep luscious red glow.\par
   \'93If you haven\'92t abandoned your suicidal crusade, I believe anything. Did you go and see Stark?\'94\par
   \'93You bet your ass, and contrary to your fears, he was very reasonable ... more than I can say about Harris or even Nelson, for that matter.\'94\par
   \'93Be careful, that\'92s all I can say. Stark is like an emotional chameleon. I usually get along with him extremely well. Yet today, out of the blue, I found out he\'92s furious at me because of some nut putting half-used medicine in a locker that I had used for a while. He doesn\'92t come to me and ask me about it the way a normal human being would. Instead he sics poor old Chandler, the chief resident, onto me, and Chandler cancels a case of mine to ask me about it Then later he calls me out of rounds to tell me Stark wants me to get to the bottom of it. You\'92d think I had nothing to do.\'94\par
   \'93What\'92s this about drugs in a locker?\'94 Susan remembered the doctor talking to Nelson.\par
   \'93I\'92m not sure I have the whole story. Something about one of the surgeons coming across a whole bunch of drugs in an OR locker which old friggin\'92 Walters still had assigned to me. Apparently there were narcotics, curare, antibiotics\'97a whole pharmacy.\'94\par
   \'93And they don\'92t know who put them there or why?\'94\par
   \'93I guess not. It\'92s my idea that somebody\'92s been saving the stuff to ship off to Biafra or Bangladesh. There\'92s always a couple of people around with some cause like that. But why they\'92ve been storing them in a locker in the lounge is beyond me.\'94\par
   \'93Curare is a nerve blocker, isn\'92t it, Mark?\'94\par
   \'93Yup, a competitive nerve blocker. A great drug. Oh, in case you haven\'92t guessed-, we\'92re dining here tonight. I got some steaks, and the hibachi is all set on the fire escape outside the kitchen window.\'94\par
   \'93Couldn\'92t be better, Mark. I\'92m exhausted. But I\'92m also hungry.\'94\par
   \'93I\'92ll put the steaks on.\'94 Mark walked into the kitchen with his wineglass.\par
   \'93Does curare depress respiration?\'94 asked Susan.\par
   \'93Nope. It just paralyzes all the muscles. The person wants to breathe but can\'92t. They suffocate.\'94\par
   Susan stared into the fireplace, resting the edge of her glass against her lower lip. The dancing flames hypnotized her and she thought about curare, about Greenly, about Berman. The fire crackled suddenly and angrily spat a red-hot coal against the screen. A piece of the coal ricocheted off the screen, landing in the rug to the side of the fireplace. Susan jumped up, flicked it off the rug and pushed it harmlessly onto the slate hearth. She then walked over to the kitchen door, watching Mark season the steaks.\par
   \'93Stark actually was interested in what I had found out and has already tried to help. I had asked him to help me get the charts of the patients on my list. When I called back later this afternoon, he said he had tried to get them for me but had been told that they were all signed out to one of the professors of neurology, a Dr. Donald McLeary. Do you know him?\'94\par
   \'93No, but that doesn\'92t mean anything. I don\'92t know very many of the nonsurgical types.\'94\par
   \'93To my way of thinking, it makes McLeary look rather suspicious.\'94\par
   \'93Oh oh, here we go again, imagination plus! Dr. Donald McLeary mysteriously destroys  the cerebrum of six patients ...\'94\par
   \'93Twelve ...\'94\par
   \'93OK, twelve, and then he signs all their charts out to eliminate any chance of suspicion. I can just picture all this in the headlines of the Boston Globe.\'94\par
   Mark laughed as he put the steaks on the hibachi through the open window, then drew it down against the cold.\par
   \'93Go ahead and laugh, but at the same time come up with an explanation for McLeary. Everyone else so far has expressed surprise at the idea of relating all these cases together. Everyone except this Dr. McLeary. He has all the charts. I just think it\'92s worth looking into. Maybe he\'92s been investigating this thing for some time and he\'92s far ahead of me. That would be nice to believe and if so, maybe I could help him.\'94\par
   Mark didn\'92t answer. He was wondering exactly how he was going to try to talk Susan out of the whole business. He was also concentrating on the salad dressing, his culinary specialty. When he reopened the kitchen window, the cold wind brought in the sizzling aroma of the cooking steaks. Susan leaned against the door frame, watching him. She thought about how marvelous it would be to have a wife, to be able to come home and have a wife keeping the house in order, the meals on the table. At the same time it seemed ridiculously unfair that she could never have a wife. It was a mental game that Susan played with herself, always to the same impasse, as which time she would simply deny the whole problem or at least postpone it until some indeterminate future date.\par
   \'93I called the Jefferson Institute today.\'94\par
   \'93What\'92d they have to say?\'94 Mark handed Susan some plates, silver and napkins, and pointed toward the onyx table.\par
   \'93You were right about it being difficult to visit,\'94 said Susan, carrying the material to the table. \'93I asked if I could come out: and visit the facility because I wanted to see one of the patients. They laughed. They told me that only the very immediate family can visit and only on prearranged, brief visits. They said that the mass methods of taking care of the patients is generally unacceptable, emotionally, to the families, so they have to make special arrangements for them to visit. They did tell me about the monthly tour you mentioned. My being a medical student counted about the same as a wooden nickel, so far as making them alter their routine. Actually the place sounds interesting, especially since, as you say, the concept has been successful in keeping chronic cases from taking up acute-care beds in the local hospitals.\'94\par
   Susan finished setting the table, then returned to staring into the fire. \'93I\'92d really like to visit, though, mostly to see Berman once more. I have a feeling that if I saw him again that I\'92d probably be able to ease up on this ... crusade, as you call it. Even I realize I\'92ve got to get back to a semblance of normality.\'94\par
   Mark straightened up from his activities in the kitchen at this last sentence, entertaining a ray of hope. He turned the steaks over again and closed the window.\par
   \'93Why don\'92t you just show up there? I mean, it must be like any other hospital when it comes right down to it. It\'92s probably as chaotic as the Memorial. If you acted like you belong, probably nobody would even question you. You could even wear a nurse\'92s uniform. If anybody came into the Memorial dressed like a doctor or & nurse, they could go anywhere they chose.\'94\par
   Susan looked back at Mark, who was standing in the kitchen door.\par
   \'93That\'92s not a bad idea ... not bad. But there\'92s a catch.\'94\par
   \'93What\'92s that?\'94\par
   \'93Simply that I wouldn\'92t know where the hell I was going even if I were able to walk into the building. It\'92s hard to look like you belong when you\'92re totally lost.\'94\par
   \'93That\'92s not an insurmountable obstacle. All you\'92d have to do is visit the building department in City Hall and get a copy of the building plans or floor plans. There are plans on file of all public buildings. You\'92d have yourself a map.\'94\par
   Mark returned to the kitchen to get the steaks and the salad.\par
   \'93Mark, that\'92s ingenious.\'94\par
   \'93Practical, not ingenious.\'94 He brought the food into the room and served up the steaks and a generous helping of salad. There were also asparagus with hollandaise sauce and another whole bottle of red Bordeaux.\par
   Each thought the meal perfect. The wine tended to smooth any potential rough edges, and the conversation flowed freely as each learned bits and pieces of the other\'92s background to fill in the gaps of the personality mosaics each was constructing of the other. Susan from Maryland, Mark from California. There was little intellectual common ground, for Mark\'92s education had been severely skewed in the direction of Descartes and Newton, while Susan\'92s tended toward Voltaire and Chaucer. But skiing emerged as a love of both, as well as the beach, and the outdoors in general. And they both liked Hemingway. There was an awkward silence after Susan asked about Joyce. Bellows had not read Joyce.\par
   With the dishes cleared, they settled on a random grouping of pillows before the fireplace at the far end of the room. Bellows put on some additional oak logs, turning the smoldering embers into a crackling blaze. Grand Marnier and Fred\'92s Home Made vanilla ice cream made them quiet for some moments, both enjoying the peaceful and contented silence.\par
   \'93Susan, getting to know you just a little better, and liking every minute of it, makes me even more motivated to urge you to forget this coma problem,\'94 said Mark, after a while. \'93You\'92ve got an enormous amount of learning to do, and believe me, there\'92s no place better than the Memorial. In all likelihood this coma problem will be around for some time, plenty of time for you to begin again when you have a real background in clinical medicine. I\'92m not trying to suggest you cannot contribute; maybe you can. But the chances of making a contribution are small, just like in any research project, no matter how well conceived. And you have to consider the effect your activities will undoubtedly have, in fact already have had, on your superiors. It\'92s a poor gamble, Susan; the odds are stacked against you.\'94\par
   Susan sipped her Grand Marnier. The viscous, smooth fluid slid down her throat, and sent warm sensations down her legs. She took in a deep breath and felt a certain levitation.\par
   \'93Being a female medical student must be hard enough,\'94 continued Bellows, \'93without adding a further handicap.\'94\par
   Susan raised her head and looked at Bellows. He was staring into the fire. \'93Exactly what do you mean by that statement?\'94 asked Susan with a sudden slight edge to her voice. Bellows was suddenly brushing against sensitive areas.\par
   \'93Just what I said.\'94 Bellows did not look up from the fire. The dancing flames had captured his attention. \'93I just think it must be particularly difficult being a female medical student. I never really thought too much about it until you forced me to come up with an alternative explanation for Harris\'92s behavior. Now, the more I think about it, the more I think I am right because ... well, to be truthful, I can\'92t say I reacted to you as a medical student first. As soon as I saw you, I reacted to you as a woman, and maybe in kind of an immature way. I mean I found you immediately attractive\'97not seductive.\'94 Bellows added the last comment quickly and turned to make sure Susan appreciated his reference to their previous conversation in the coffee shop.\par
   Susan smiled. The defensive attitude, which Bellows\'92s initial statement had rekindled, had melted.\par
   \'93That was why I reacted so foolishly when you walked into the dressing room yesterday and caught me in my shorts. If I had thought of you asexually, I wouldn\'92t have budged. But it was pretty apparent that was not the case. Anyway, I think most of your professors and instructors are going to react to you first as female and only second as a student of medicine.\'94\par
   Bellows looked back into the fire; he almost had the attitude of a contrite sinner who has confessed. Susan felt a resurgence of the warmth she had begun to feel toward him. She felt again the urge to give him one of her people hugs, as she thought of them. In truth Susan was a physical person, although she did not show it often, especially since entering medicine. Even before applying to medical school, Susan had decided that the physical aspects of her personality had to be suppressed if she was going to make it in medicine. Now instead of reaching for Mark, she sipped her Grand Marnier.\par
   \'93Susan, you are very apparent in any group and if you don\'92t show up at my lecture, I\'92m going to have to account for you.\'94\par
   \'93The luxury of anonymity,\'94 said Susan, \'93has not been something I could enjoy ever since I started medical school. I understand what you are saying, Mark. At the same time I feel I need just one more day. One more.\'94 Susan held up one finger and tilted her head in a coquettish fashion. Then she laughed.\par
   \'93You know, Mark, it is reassuring to hear you say that you think being a female medical student is difficult, because it is. Some of the girls in my class deny it, but they\'92re fooling themselves. They\'92re using one of the oldest and easiest defense mechanisms;, get around a problem by saying it\'92s not there. But it is. I remember reading a quote by Sir William Osier. He said there were three classes of human beings: men, women, and women physicians. I laughed when I read that the first time. Now I don\'92t laugh anymore.\par
   \'93Despite the feminist movement there still lingers the conventional image of wide-eyed feminine naivet\'e9 and all that bullshit. As soon as you enter a field which demands a bit of competitive and aggressive action, the men all label you as a castrating bitch. If you sit back and try to use passive, compliant behavior, you find yourself being told that you can\'92t respond to the competitive atmosphere. So you\'92re forced to try to find your own compromise somewhere in the middle, which is difficult because all the while you feel like you\'92re on trial, not as an individual but as a representative of women in general.\'94\par
   There was silence for a few moments, each digesting what had been said.\par
   \'93The thing that bothers me the most,\'94 added Susan, \'93is that the problem gets worse, not better, the farther, into medicine one goes. I cannot imagine how these women with families do it. They have to apologize for leaving work early and then they have to apologize for getting home late, no matter what time it is. I mean, the man can work late, no problem, in fact it makes him seem that much more dedicated. But a woman physician: her role is so diffuse. Society and its conventional female mores make it very difficult.\par
   \'93How did you get me on this platform?\'94 asked Susan suddenly, realizing the vehemence with which she had been speaking.\par
   \'93You were just agreeing to my statement that being a female medical student was difficult. So how about agreeing to the last part, about not taking on any more handicaps?\'94\par
   \'93Shit, Mark, don\'92t push me right at this moment. Obviously you can see that once I got involved in this thing, I probably need to resolve it somehow. Maybe it\'92s related to my feeling like I\'92m on trial for women. God, I\'92d like to show that Harris where to get off. Maybe if I can see Berman again, I\'92ll be able to give up without any loss of intellectual face or ... what should I say, self-image or self-confidence. But let\'92s talk about something else. Would you mind if I were to give you a hug?\'94\par
   \'93Me, mind?\'94 Bellows sat up quickly but slightly flustered. \'93Not at all.\'94\par
   Susan leaned over and gave him a squeeze with a force that surprised him. Instinctively his arms went around her and he felt her narrow back. Somewhat self-consciously he patted it, as if he were comforting her. She pulled back.\par
   \'93I hope you\'92re not waiting for me to burp.\'94\par
   For several moments they studied each other in the firelight. Then tentatively their lips sought each other, gently at first, then with obvious emotion, finally with abandon.\par
Wednesday, February 25, 5:45 A.M.\par
The alarm jangled in the darkness, making the air in the room vibrate with its piercing sound. Susan sat bolt upright from a dead sleep. At first she wondered why her eyes wouldn\'92t open; then she realized that they were open. It was just that they could not pierce the utter blackness in the room. For several seconds she had no idea where she was. Her only thought was to try to find the alarm clock and deaden its awful nerve-shattering noise.\par
   As suddenly as it had started, it stopped with a metallic click. At the same time Susan became conscious that she was not alone. The memory of the previous evening swept over her, and she remembered that she was still at Mark\'92s apartment. She lay back, bringing up the covers to cover her nakedness.\par
   \'93What in God\'92s name was that noise for?\'94 said Susan to the blackness.\par
   \'93It\'92s an alarm. I suppose you\'92ve never heard one before,\'94 said a voice from beside her.\par
   \'93An alarm. Mark, it\'92s the middle of the night.\'94\par
   \'93Like hell it is; it\'92s five-thirty and time to get rolling.\'94\par
   Mark threw back the covers and put his feet onto the floor. He turned on the lamp next to the bed and rubbed his eyes.\par
   \'93Mark, you\'92ve got to be out of your squash. Five-thirty, Christ.\'94 The voice was muffled; Susan had her head underneath the pillow.\par
   \'93I\'92ve got to see my patients, grab a bit to eat, and be ready for rounds at six-thirty. Surgery starts at seven-thirty sharp.\'94 Mark stood up and stretched. Disregarding his nakedness and the coldness, he started for the bathroom.\par
   \'93You surgical masochists defy imagination. Why don\'92t you start at nine or some other reasonable time? Why seven-thirty?\'94\par
   \'93It\'92s always been seven-thirty,\'94 said Bellows, pausing in the doorway.\par
   \'93That\'92s a great reason. It\'92s seven-thirty because it\'92s always been seven-thirty\'97God, it\'92s that type of reasoning that\'92s so typical in medicine. Five-thirty in the morning. Shit, Mark, why didn\'92t you tell me about this when you invited me to stay last night? I would have gone back to the dorm.\'94\par
   Bellows walked back to the bedside, looking down at the mound of covers indicating Susan\'92s body. The pillow was still over her head.\par
   \'93If you\'92d take your surgical rotation a bit more seriously, I wouldn\'92t have to tell you what is the normal modus operandi. Time to get up, beauty queen.\'94\par
   Bellows grabbed the edge of the blankets and, with a forceful jerk, pulled all the covers from the bed, leaving Susan bared to the elements, except for her head, still concealed by the pillow.\par
   \'93Some hospitality,\'94 said Susan, jumping up. She grabbed a blanket and twisted herself into an instant cocoon, then collapsed back onto the bed.\par
   \'93Ah, but today is the first day of your new leaf. You\'92re going to be a normal medical student.\'94\par
   A tug of war ensued with Susan\'92s wrapping.\par
   \'93I need one more full day, just one. Come on, Mark, one more. You can understand that it\'92s important for me. If I don\'92t get the charts today, which I think I won\'92t, then it\'92s all over. Besides, if I can see Berman, I\'92ll probably give up. Then you\'92ll have your normal medical student. But I need one more day.\'94\par
   Bellows let go of the blankets. Susan fell back, one breast exposed in a fetching Amazonian way.\par
   \'93All right, one more day. But if Stark is on rounds today, he\'92ll know that you are phantomizing. I wouldn\'92t be able to come up with any cover story. I hope you realize that.\'94\par
   \'93Let\'92s just play it by ear, almighty surgeon. I\'92m sure you\'92ll think of something.\'94\par
   \'93Susan, I\'92ll just have to say that I had told you to be on rounds.\'94\par
   \'93OK, have it your way. But I\'92m spending one more whole day on this thing. I\'92ve got some investment into it already.\'94\par
   Susan snuggled into the warm bed. She barely heard the shower start in the bathroom. She thought she\'92d wait until Bellows finished before getting up.\par
   \par
   When Susan awoke the second time, it was already quite light. Sudden gusts of wind blew rain against the window panes with a sound like rice hitting glass. With a contrariness typical of Boston weather, the wind had shifted during the night from northwest to due east. Thanks to the Gulf Stream, the temperature had risen into the high thirties, so precipitation was in the liquid rather than solid phase. The commuters were relieved, the skiers disgusted.\par
   It was hard for Susan to believe the clock next to the bed, because it said almost nine. Bellows had showered, dressed, and exited without having reawakened her. Susan was amazed, for she was a relatively light sleeper. Just to be sure, she checked the bathroom and the living room for any sign that Bellows might still be there. She was alone.\par
   Susan found a clean towel, then showered vigorously, remembering the previous night\'92s passion with a pleasant sense of warmth. Bellows had turned out to be a far more sensitive and innately generous lover than Susan had surmised. She was genuinely pleased, although she had some serious reservations about the relationship going very far. Bellows\'92s commitment to surgery seemed somehow too encompassing, as if everything else in his life would necessarily be relegated to a secondary position like a hobby.\par
   In the refrigerator, Susan found some cheese and an orange. She helped herself to Grapenuts and toast while thumbing through the Yellow Pages. Checking to be sure that she had everything, she left Bellows\'92s apartment, locking the door securely behind her. It was going to be a busy day.\par
   The rain had let up significantly by the time Susan hit the street. The weather did not appear to be clearing, but now it would be more pleasant to walk about. Susan turned left up Mt. Vernon toward the State House. She crossed the Boston Common at its northern tip and entered the downtown shopping area.\par
   Of all the young girls who had come to the Boston Uniform Company retail store seeking a nurse\'92s uniform, the salesman found Susan the easiest and fastest customer. She seemed totally uninterested in the bewildering permutations of the plain white dress. She asked for size ten and told the salesman that any size ten would do.\par
   \'93We have this style here which you might like,\'94 he said, bringing out one uniform.\par
   Susan took the dress and held it against herself as she looked into the mirror.\par
   \'93The changing rooms are in the back if you\'92d like to try it.\'94\par
   \'93I\'92ll take it.\'94\par
   The salesman was stunned if gratified at the speed of the sale.\par
   \par
   The rain started again half-heartedly as Susan walked up Washington Street toward Government Center. As she reached the middle of the bricked mall in front of the ultra-geometric City Hall, the wind brought in another moisture-laden cloud over the city. As the rain came down in earnest Susan ran for cover.\par
   The girl at the information booth told Susan that the building department was on the eighth floor. It was easy to find. Once there, though, things were different. Susan waited for twenty-five minutes at the main counter only to be told that she was at the wrong place. This happened twice before she was directed to the rear of the vast room. There was another wait of a quarter of an hour despite the fact she was the only customer. Behind the counter were five desks, of which three were occupied. Two men and one woman. The two men looked surprisingly alike, with large red noses, plastic black-rimmed glasses, and tasteless ties. They were engaged in a heated argument about the Patriots. The woman had a ratted hairdo recalling the early sixties and shocking red lipstick that used the natural lip borders only as suggestions. She was engrossed with a pocket mirror, examining her face from every possible angle.\par
   The smaller of the two men eventually eyed Susan and realized that she was not going to disappear despite the fact that she was being ignored. He rambled over, uninterested. When he reached the counter he took his cigarette from his mouth. A few of the ashes from the tip dusted down the front of his tie. He crushed the butt repeatedly in a cheap and already overflowing metal ashtray.\par
   \'93What can I do for you?\'94 said the bureaucrat, looking at Susan for a moment. He turned before she could answer.\par
   \'93Hey, Harry, that reminds me. What are you going to do about the GRI 5 request? Remember, it was filed as urgent and it\'92s been in your box for two months.\'94 Looking back at Susan, \'93What is it, honey? Let me guess. You want to file a complaint about your landlord. Well, this isn\'92t the right place.\'94\par
   He looked back at his colleague. \'93Harry, if you\'92re going for coffee, pick me up a regular and a Danish. I\'92ll pay you later.\'94 His red eyes turned to Susan. \'93Now then ...\'94\par
   \'93I\'92d like to look at some plans; the floor plans for the Jefferson Institute. It\'92s a relatively new hospital in South Boston.\'94\par
   \'93Plans. What do you want plans for? How old are you, fifteen?\'94\par
   \'93I\'92m a medical student and I\'92m interested in hospital design and construction.\'94\par
   \'93Kids today! With your looks you don\'92t have to be interested in anything.\'94 He laughed obnoxiously.\par
   Susan closed her eyes, resisting the retort the comment deserved.\par
   The state employee started toward a stack of oversized books on the counter. \'93What ward is it in?\'94 he asked with obvious ennui.\par
   \'93I haven\'92t the slightest idea.\'94\par
   \'93All right then,\'94 said the man, making an about-face. \'93First we\'92ll have to find out which ward it is in.\'94\par
   A smaller book on the counter supplied the needed information.\par
   \'93Ward 17.\'94\par
   With calculated slowness, he returned to the large books on the counter. From his side pocket he withdrew a crumpled pack of cigarettes. He put one cigarette in his mouth, leaving it unlit. After picking several wrong volumes, he found the Ward 17 volume. The other books were pushed aside. Turning back the cover, he slobbered over his index finger. He flipped the pages forcefully, running his finger across his tobacco-stained tongue every four of five pages. Having found the reference, he copied the figures onto a piece of scrap paper. Motioning for Susan to follow, he started toward a large bank of filing cabinets.\par
   \'93Harry!\'94 called the bureaucrat, continuing his conversation with his colleague en route to the filing cabinets, the unlit cigarette bobbing up and down in his mouth. \'93Before you go downstairs, call up Grosser and find out if Lester is coming in today. Somebody\'92s goin\'92 to have to file that stuff on his desk if he\'92s not; that\'92s been there longer than your GRI 5 request.\'94\par
   It was a simple affair to find the correct drawer and extract a large packet of plans. \'93Here you are, Goldilocks; there\'92s a Xerox machine over in that room beyond the counter, if you want. It takes nickels.\'94 He pointed with his unlit cigarette.\par
   \'93Maybe you could show me which of these are floor plans.\'94 Susan had withdrawn the contents from the jacket.\par
   \'93You\'92re interested in hospital construction and you don\'92t know what floor plans look like? My God. Here, these are the floor plans ... basement, first floor, and second floor.\'94 He lit his cigarette with a pocket lighter.\par
   \'93How do you decipher these abbreviations?\'94\par
   \'93For Christ\'92s sake, right here in the lower corner. It says \'91OR\'92, means operating room. \'91W (main)\'92; that means main ward. And \'91Comp. R.\'92 stands for computer room and so forth.\'94 The man showed signs of incipient irritation.\par
   \'93And the Xerox machine?\'94\par
   \'93Over there. There\'92s a change machine on the wall. When you finish with the plans, just put them in the metal bin on the counter.\'94\par
   Susan carefully Xeroxed the floor plans and labeled the rooms on the copy with a felt-tipped pen. Then she headed for the Memorial.\par
   \par
   Susan entered the Memorial through the main entrance. It was just after ten in the morning. Yet the inevitable daily crowds were already there. Every conceivable seat was occupied. There were people of all ages, waiting, forever waiting. These were not people seeking attention in either the clinic or the emergency room. They were people waiting for a relative to be admitted or discharged, or perhaps they were patients who had been seen and treated and were now waiting to be picked up and taken home. There was little conversation and no smiles. These were all distinct and separate islands, united only by their healthy awe of the hospital and its shrouded mysteries.\par
   The dense crowd impeded Susan\'92s progress, forcing her to push her way through to the directory. The plastic letters spelled out \'93Neurology Department, Beard 11.\'94 Susan made her way to the Beard elevators and waited with the crowd. The person next to her turned and Susan recoiled in ill-concealed horror. The man\'92s\'97or was it a woman\'92s\'97eyes were surrounded by dark areas of hemorrhage. The nose was swollen and distorted, with nasal packs partially extruding from the nostrils. Several wires came from within the nose and were taped to either check. The visage was that of a monster. Susan tried to keep her eyes on the elevator indicator, unprepared for the visual surprises of the hospital.\par
   \par
   Dr. Donald McLeary was one of the younger members of the fulltime neurology staff and, because of the ever-mounting pressure of space, had not been given an office on eleven. Susan had to take the stairs up to twelve before she found the door with \'93Dr. Donald M. McLeary\'94 stenciled on it in black letters. She opened the door and squeezed into a tiny outer office; the door could not be opened all the way because of a filing cabinet. The desk, of average size, appeared huge in the room. An aging secretary looked up. She had extraordinarily thick makeup, including rouge and false eyelashes. Her totally bleached hair was glued into short, tight curls. She wore a tight pink pants-suit outfit that strained over unnatural bulges.\par
   \'93Excuse me, is Dr. McLeary in?\'94\par
   \'93He\'92s in, but he is very busy.\'94 The secretary was annoyed at the intrusion. \'93Have you an appointment?\'94\par
   \'93No. No, I haven\'92t, but I only want to ask him a quick question. I\'92m a medical student rotating here at the Memorial.\'94\par
   \'93I\'92ll check with the doctor.\'94\par
   The secretary stood up, eyeing Susan from head to foot. Even more irritated at Susan\'92s lissome figure, she entered the inner office to Susan\'92s right. Susan looked around the outer office for any signs of the hospital charts she wanted.\par
   Almost immediately, the woman returned, sat down at her desk, put a piece of stationery into the typewriter and typed several lines. Only then did she look up.\par
   \'93You may go in; he says he has a moment for you.\'94\par
   The secretary resumed her typing before Susan could respond. Whispering some choice epithets under her breath, Susan opened the door and entered the inner office.\par
   Reminiscent of Dr. Nelson\'92s office, McLeary\'92s office was equally messy, with journals and papers in innumerable haphazard stacks. Several of the stacks had tipped over at some previous time and had never been reerected. Dr. McLeary was a thin, intense-looking man with a deep crease that ran down through the middle of each cheek. His sharply angular nose and chin were separated by a small mouth that twitched as he eyed Susan over his glasses and through his bushy eyebrows.\par
   \'93Susan Wheeler, I presume,\'94 said Dr. McLeary, with no friendliness in his voice.\par
   \'93Yes.\'94 Susan was surprised that he knew her name. She could not decide if that were propitious or not.\par
   \'93And you have come concerning these ten charts I have here.\'94 McLeary half-turned in his chair, waving toward a large group of hospital charts in his bookcase.\par
   \'93Ten? Is that all you have?\'94\par
   \'93Isn\'92t ten enough?\'94 asked McLeary somewhat sarcastically.\par
   \'93Fine. I just thought that maybe you\'92d have more. Are those the charts of the coma victims?\'94\par
   \'93Possibly. What do you have in mind if they are?\'94\par
   \'93I\'92m not sure. Dr. Stark told me you had the charts, and I thought I\'92d come by and ask if I could perhaps look at them or help you extract them.\'94\par
   \'93Young lady, I\'92m a neurologist with considerable training. My expertise is neurology, and I am evaluating the extensive neurological evaluations that were done on these patients by our resident staff. I really don\'92t need any help.\'94\par
   \'93I\'92m not insinuating that you need help, Dr. McLeary, least of all in a professional capacity. I admit that I know next to nothing about neurology. But these patients all have suffered a tragedy akin to death and there is something very strange about the whole affair. I think these cases have to be viewed in terms of some kind of association rather than as random events.\'94\par
   \'93And of course you are going to be the one to do that.\'94\par
   \'93Well, somebody has to do it.\'94\par
   McLeary paused and Susan had the uncomfortable feeling that the conversation was rapidly deteriorating.\par
   \'93Well, let me tell you this,\'94 continued McLeary with a forceful quality to his voice. \'93This kind of a problem is far broader than your current capabilities. Not only that, but your efforts so far are already responsible for a disproportionate amount of trouble in this hospital. Rather than a help you are fast becoming a definite handicap. What I want you to do now is sit down.\'94 McLeary pointed to one of the chairs in front of his desk.\par
   \'93I beg your pardon?\'94 Susan had heard but the tone was confusing. McLeary wasn\'92t asking; he was ordering.\par
   \'93I said, sit down!\'94 The anger in his voice now was unmistakable.\par
   Susan sat down in the only chair without a complement of journal articles.\par
   McLeary picked up the phone and dialed. He looked directly at Susan with unblinking, beady eyes. \'91His mouth twitched as he waited for a connection.\par
   \'93Director\'92s office, please. ... I\'92d like to speak to Philip Oren.\'94\par
   There was a longer pause. McLeary\'92s expression did not change.\par
   \'93Mr. Oren, Dr. McLeary here. You were quite right. She is sitting here in front of me. ... The charts? Of course not, you must be joking ... All right ... fine.\'94\par
   McLeary hung up the phone, still looking directly at Susan. Susan could not detect even an iota of human warmth. She thought that he deserved the secretary he had. After an awkward silence Susan started to get up.\par
   \'93I have a feeling that I should not ...\'94\par
   \'93Sit down!\'94  shouted McLeary even more loudly than before.\par
   Susan sat down quickly, surprised at the sudden outburst.\par
   \'93What is going on here? I came in here to see if you could use some help in looking into the coma problem, not to be shouted at.\'94\par
   \'93I really have nothing more to say to you, young lady. You have overstepped your boundaries here at the Memorial. I was told that you would probably come snooping for these charts. I was also told you obtained unauthorized information from the computer. And on top of that, you managed to alienate Dr. Harris. Anyway, Mr. Oren will be here in a moment and you can talk with him. This is his problem, not mine.\'94\par
   \'93Who is Mr. Oren?\'94\par
   \'93The director, of the hospital, my young friend. He is the administrator, and personnel problems are in his bailiwick.\'94\par
   \'93I\'92m not personnel. I\'92m a medical student.\'94\par
   \'93True enough. And that actually puts you on somewhat of a lower plane. You are a guest here ... a guest of the hospital ... and as such, your conduct should be suitable to the hospitality extended to you. Instead you have chosen to be disruptive and to ignore rules and regulations. You medical students of today somehow have gotten your sense of position in the scheme of things reversed. The hospital does not exist for your benefit. The hospital does not owe you an education.\'94\par
   \'93This is a teaching hospital and is associated with the medical school. Teaching is supposed to be one of the major functions of this hospital.\'94\par
   \'93Teaching, of course, but that certainly doesn\'92t mean just medical students. It means the whole medical community.\'94\par
   \'93Exactly. Supposedly it is a symbiotic atmosphere for everyone\'92s benefit: student and professor alike. The hospital doesn\'92t exist for the benefit of the medical student nor for the benefit of the professor. In fact, it\'92s supposed to be primarily for the patient.\'94\par
   \'93Well, it is indeed easy to understand Harris\'92s reaction to you, Miss Wheeler. As he said, you lack respect for people as well as institutions. But it is a reflection of youth in general today. They believe their very existence alone entitles them to all the luxuries of society, education being one of them.\'94\par
   \'93Education is more than a luxury; it is a responsibility that society owes to itself.\'94\par
   \'93Society undoubtedly has a responsibility to itself but not to individual students, not to youth just because they are youth. Education is a luxury in that it is expensive beyond belief and the major burden, particularly in medicine, falls on the public at large, the workingman. The students themselves pay a small amount of the money needed. Not only does it cost an enormous amount of money to have you here, Miss Wheeler, but your being here means that you are economically unproductive. Hence the cost to society automatically doubles. And besides, your being a woman means that your future per-hour productivity ...\'94\par
   \'93Oh save me,\'94 said Susan sarcastically, standing up. \'93I\'92ve heard about as much bullshit as I can stand.\'94\par
   \'93Stay put, young lady,\'94 shouted McLeary, furious. He too stood up.\par
   Susan tried to look behind the face of the man trembling with anger in front of her. She thought about Bellows\'92s suggestion relative to sexuality explaining Harris\'92s behavior. She was hard put to believe that was a factor in McLeary\'92s performance. Once again she was facing very irregular behavior, to say the least. The man was breathing rapidly, his chest heaving. She had apparently and unknowingly challenged the man. But how? In what capacity? She had no idea. Susan debated whether she should just walk out. A mixture of curiosity and respect for the apparent irrationality of McLeary\'92s actions made her stay. She sat down, watching McLeary, who now couldn\'92t decide what to do. He too sat down and began nervously playing with an ashtray. Susan sat motionless. She wouldn\'92t have been surprised if the man cried.\par
   She heard the outer office door opening. Voices drifted into the inner office. Then the inner office door opened. Without being announced or knocking, an energetic individual entered. He appeared like a businessman, in a smartly tailored blue suit. Reminding Susan of Stark\'92s attire, a silk handkerchief peeked out of his left breast pocket. His hair was carefully combed and frozen with a ruler-straight part on the left side. There was a definite aura of authority about the man; he exuded an air of assurance at handling a wide spectrum of problems.\par
   \'93Thank you for your call, Donald,\'94 said Oren.\par
   Then he faced Susan condescendingly.\par
   \'93So this is the infamous Susan Wheeler. Miss Wheeler, you have been causing a great commotion in this hospital. Are you aware of that?\'94\par
   \'93No, I haven\'92t been aware of that.\'94\par
   Oren leaned back on McLeary\'92s desk, folding his arms in a professional fashion.\par
   \'93Out of curiosity, Miss Wheeler, let me ask you a rather simple question. What do you think is the major goal of this institution?\'94\par
   \'93Caring for the sick.\'94\par
   \'93Good. At least we agree in general. But I must add a crucial phrase to your answer. We are caring for the sick of this community. That might sound redundant to you because obviously we are not caring for the sick of Westchester County, New York. Yet this is an extremely important distinction because it underlines our responsibility to the people right here in Boston. As a direct corollary, anything that could interrupt or otherwise disturb this relationship to the community would, in effect, negate our primary mission. Now this may sound very ... what should I say ... irrelevant to you. But quite the contrary. I have been receiving complaints about you over the last few days which have grown from being irritated to intolerable. Apparently you are bent on specifically disrupting our carefully maintained relationship with the community.\'94\par
   Susan felt color rising in her cheeks. Oren\'92s condescending manner began to irritate her.\par
   \'93I suppose bringing to the forefront of everyone\'92s awareness that the chances of becoming a vegetable, of losing one\'92s brain, is very high, intolerably high, by being a patient here would ruin the reputation of the hospital.\'94\par
   \'93Exactly.\'94\par
   \'93Well, it seems to me that the reputation of the hospital is nothing compared to the irreparable damage suffered by these people. I have become more and more convinced that the reputation of the hospital deserves to be ruined if that\'92s what it takes to solve the problem.\'94\par
   \'93Now, Miss Wheeler, you can\'92t be serious. Where would all the people turn ... all the people who are in daily need of the facilities in this hospital? Come ... come. And by glibly drawing attention to an unfortunate but nevertheless unavoidable complication ...\'94\par
   \'93How do you know it\'92s unavoidable?\'94 interrupted Susan.\par
   \'93I can only believe what the chiefs of the respective departments assure me. I am not a doctor nor a scientist, Miss Wheeler, nor do I pretend to be. I am an administrator. And when I am faced with a medical student who is here to learn surgery, but instead spends her time calling attention to a problem which is already under investigation by qualified people such as Dr. McLeary here\'97a problem whose indiscreet disclosure has the potential to cause irreparable harm to the community, I am forced to react quickly and decisively. Obviously the warnings and exhortations you have already received to assume your normal duties have gone unheeded. But this is not a debate. I\'92m not here to argue with you. On the contrary, with all due respect, I thought it best to give you an explanation for my decision about your surgery rotation. Now, if you\'92ll excuse me, I will phone your dean of students.\'94\par
   Oren picked up McLeary\'92s telephone and dialed.\par
   \'93Dr. Chapman\'92s office, please. ... Dr. Chapman, please. Phil Oren calling. ... Jim, Phil Oren here. How\'92s the family? Everyone in our house is just fine. ... I suppose I told you that Ted\'92s been accepted at the University of Pennsylvania. ... I hope so. ... The reason I called is about one of your third-year students rotating on surgery, a Susan Wheeler. ... That\'92s right. ... Sure, I\'92ll hold.\'94\par
   Oren looked at Susan. \'93You are a third-year student, Miss Wheeler?\'94\par
   Susan nodded. Her nascent anger had melted into dejection.\par
   Oren looked back at McLeary, who suddenly stood up, apparently bored. \'93I\'92m sorry, Don, for this intrusion,\'94 said Oren. \'93I suppose we should have gone to my office. I\'92ll be finished ...\'94 Oren redirected his attention into the telephone. \'93Yes, I\'92m here, Jim ... well that\'92s nice to know she\'92s been a good student. But nonetheless she had exhausted her welcome here at the Memorial. She is supposed to be on surgery but has decided never to attend rounds, conferences, or surgery. Instead, she has been irritating the staff, particularly our Chief of Anesthesia, and exacting unauthorized information from our computer storage facility by some devious means. We obviously have enough trouble around here without her kind of help. ... Sure, I\'92ll tell her you want to see her ... this afternoon at four-thirty. Good enough. I\'92m sure the V.A. would be happy to have her ... right (chuckle). Thanks, Jim. Speak to you soon, and let\'92s get together.\'94\par
   Oren hung up the phone and smiled diplomatically at McLeary. Then he turned to Susan.\par
   \'93Miss Wheeler, your dean, as you have plainly heard, would like to have a word with you this afternoon at four-thirty. From this moment on, your professional welcome at the Memorial has been terminated. Goodbye.\'94\par
   Susan looked from Oren to McLeary and then back. Mc-Leary\'92s expression was unchanged. Oren sported a self-satisfied smile, as if he had just won a debate. There was an awkward silence. Susan realized that the scene was over, and she got up without a word, picked up the parcel containing the nurse\'92s uniform, and left.\par
Wednesday, February 25, 11:15 A.M.\par
Finding the hospital intolerably oppressive from an emotional point of view, Susan fled. She pushed her way through the lingering crowds, out into the rainy, raw February day. Once outside and without any particular destination in mind, she just walked, aimlessly, lost in her own thoughts. She turned on New Chardon Street and then on Cambridge Street.\par
   \'93Assholes,\'94 she hissed as she kicked a stray, partially crunched Campbell\'92s soup can. The light rain flattened her hair against her forehead. Small droplets coalesced and dripped from the tip of her nose. She wandered up Joy Street into the back side of Beacon Hill, preoccupied with her stream of consciousness. She saw but her mind did not record the clutter of life, dogs, garbage, and other debris of the decaying urban surroundings.\par
   She could not remember ever feeling quite so rejected and isolated. She felt totally alone, and sudden fears of failure kept reoccurring in her compulsively conditioned brain. Waves of depression alternated with anger as she went over the conversations with McLeary and Oren. She yearned to talk with someone, someone whose counsel she could trust and respect Stark, Bellows, Chapman; each was a possibility but each had a specific disadvantage. Bellows\'92s objectivity would have to be suspect; Stark\'92s and Chapman\'92s overriding loyalties would be to their respective institutions.\par
   Susan thought of the worst: being dismissed from medical school in disgrace. Not only would it be a personal failure but she felt it would be a failure for all women in medicine. Susan wished there were some woman doctor to whom she could turn, but she did not know any. There were so few on the medical school staff, and none in any positions that made them accessible for counseling.\par
   In the middle of her tormented musing, Susan felt her right foot slide as she put her weight on it. She had to steady herself with her hand on a nearby building to keep from falling. Expecting the worst, she looked down to see that she had stepped in a large steaming pile of dog feces.\par
   \'93God damn Beacon Hill.\'94 Susan cursed Boston and all the literal and figurative shit a city government tolerated. Using the curb to dislodge most of the material, Susan choked on the odor. Still she couldn\'92t help but think about the symbolic aspect of her misfortune. Perhaps she had been stepping into a pile of shit, and as she was forced to do in regard to the actual shit in the city, she should try to ignore the whole affair. Just walk around it. Her responsibility was to become a doctor; that should take precedence over everything. The Bermans and the Greenlys were not her concern.\par
   The rain continued and rivulets ran down her cheeks. She began to walk more carefully, prudently noticing the innumerable piles of dog crap that characterized Beacon Hill as much as the gas lamps or the red brick. She watched where she put her feet and the going was easier. But she could not dismiss her sense of responsibility to the Bermans and the Greenlys so easily. She thought about the age similarity between herself and Nancy Greenly. She thought about her own periods and the several episodes when she had bled more heavily than usual; how it had frightened her and made her feel helpless and out of control. She might have had to have a D&C herself, possibly at the Memorial.\par
   But now she was out of the Memorial, maybe out of medical school. There was little that was up to her at that point, whether she wanted to pursue the problem or not. It was finished. It embarrassed her slightly to think of the frame of mind she had when she started the affair. \'93A new disease!\'94 Susan laughed at her own vanity and deluded sense of ability.\par
